figgy.title: File appender failure notices are too frequent

comments.body:
One thing I notice is that even when there are failed derivatives for these resources, there's not the banner message "x/y derivatives generated" or whatever it says that cues ingesters to know there may be an issue. If they're looking for that and not scanning through the actual file list or viewer they won't notice these problems.

Error analysis.

- "multipart upload failed" (note nested Net::OpenTimeout errors): Needed derivatives regenerated. Steps I took: Use the resource id to get to the resource in figgy, click through to its parent, go to file manager, click "regenerate derivatives" button for the corresponding file.
  - some of these were fine; may have been regenerated by ingester
- Net::OpenTimeout
  - one was fine (although it may have been regenerated by ingester)
  - some others needed derivatives regenerated
- "multipart upload failed: The difference between the request time and the current time is too large.": needed derivatives regenerated
- "SSL_connect SYSCALL returned=5 errno=0 state=SSLv3/TLS write client hello": needed derivatives regenerated
- "multipart upload failed: SSL_connect SYSCALL returned=5 errno=0 state=SSLv3/TLS write client hello": needed derivatives regenerated
- "execution expired": needed derivatives regenerated
- "multipart upload failed: Your socket connection to the server was not read from or written to within the timeout period. Idle connections will be closed.": needed derivatives generated; several of these
- "multipart upload failed: Connection reset by peer": needed derivatives regenerated
- "The AWS Access Key Id you provided does not exist in our records.": this stemmed from key rotation event but nothing needed to be regenerated. not sure if someone else did that.
- "multipart upload failed: Failed to open TCP connection to iiif-image-production.s3.amazonaws.com:443 (getaddrinfo: Temporary failure in name resolution)"
  - needed to be regenerated
 
This one was not something I had seen before.
- multipart upload failed: undefined method `read' for #<IngestableFile:0x0000555f3e839558>
  - created https://github.com/pulibrary/figgy/issues/5352
No, this is not right. Looks like files are not being cleaned up when derivatives are regenerated.
there are 586 of these. I'm working on extracting a list of ids.

comments.body:
@Bess (@kelynch fyi ) I think we are going to need to talk further about how the metadata in Dublin Core will be translated to Datacite. There are cases where this may not move neatly. 

For example, Neggin shared this record with me: [Supplement to PhD Dissertation: "Subsurface Computational Modeling and Policy Analysis of Large-Scale Carbon Capture, Utilization, and Storage (2022)"](https://dataspace.princeton.edu/handle/88435/dsp01n870zt98h)

"Referenced By" in Neggin's example and "Related Publication" in Bess's example (if an ID is available for the publication) may both fall under the "RelatedIdentifer" property in Datacite, but may use different selections from the controlled lists in the subproperties. (See: [RelatedIdentifier in Datacite 4.4](https://support.datacite.org/docs/datacite-metadata-schema-v44-recommended-and-optional-properties#12a-relatedidentifiertype)) As is, Bess's example might use "Related Item" for a better fit to Datacite. (See: [Related Item property in Datacite 4.4](https://support.datacite.org/docs/datacite-metadata-schema-v44-recommended-and-optional-properties#20-relateditem)) 

**It will be important to check that both of these fields in Dublin Core/DataSpace have been used consistently, before assuming which of the aforementioned Datacite properties should be applied.**  

Additionally, we should discuss whether some Dublin Core properties have information that we don't want transferred to Datacite. These might contain information that isn't needed or desired in the new infrastructure. For example, I think Wind will have some thoughts on "Collection" for the main collection. However, these may be important to keep in place for PPPL. In Bess's example, "Description" is capturing an auto-generated message about the README that might not be useful -- but that's something we need to discuss.
